description: TO PASS THE SENATE RESOLUTION PROVIDING THAT THE HONORABLE JAMES LAMMAN, APPOINTED A SENATOR BY THE GOVERNOR OF THE STATE OF CONNECTICUT, BE ADMITTED TO TAKE OATH REQUIRED BY THE CONSTITUTION.
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION TO CONFIRM THE APPOINTMENT OF HENRY CLAY AS SECRETARY OF STATE.
TO REMOVE THE INJUNCTION OF SECRECY FROM THE PROCEEDINGS REGARDING THE RATIFICATION OF THE NOMINATION OF HENRY CLAY AS SECRETARY OF STATE.
TO PASS AN AMENDED RESOLUTION CONCERNING PURCHASE OF COPIES OF JOURNALS OF THE OLD CONGRESS TO BE DISTRIBUTED AMONG PRESENT AND PAST MEMBERS OF THE SENATE.
TO RATIFY THE FIRST ARTICLE OF A TREATY WITH THE REPUBLIC OF COLUMBIA, MOTION MADE IN COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING THE FIRST ARTICLE OF A TREATY WITH THE REPUBLIC OF COLUMBIA.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION TO RATIFY THE TREATY WITH THE REPUBLIC OF COLUMBIA, WITH THE EXECPTION OF THE FIRST ARTICLE.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION THAT THERE BE ADDED TO THE 30TH RULE FOR CONDUCTING THE BUSINESS OF THE SENATE A PROVISION FOR A NEW COMMITTEE, TO BE CALLED THE COMMITTEE ON AGRICULTURE.
TO ADOPT THE RESOLUTION TO RATIFY THE TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE GREAT AND LITTLE OSAGE TRIBES OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE KAUZAS NATION OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE SHAWNEE NATION OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY OF PEACE, AMITY, COMMERCE, AND NAVIGATION BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE FEDERATION OF THE CENTER OF AMERICA.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF A SENATE BILL ENTITLED:  "PREVENTION OF DESERTION AND TO ENCOURAGE ENLISTMENT IN THE ARMY."

TO CONCUR IN THE AMENDMENT TO SENATE BILL "TO SECURE THE ACCOUNTABILITY OF PUBLIC OFFICERS AND OTHERS" BY ELIMINATING THE THIRD SECTION:  "THAT NO PERSON SHALL BE APPOINTED A COLLECTOR OR RECEIVER WHO SHALL, AT THE TIME OF APPOINTMENT, BE INDEBTED TO THEU.S."
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE PONCHAR TRIBE OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE TETON, YANCTON, AND YANCTONIES BANDS OF THE SIOUX TRIBE OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE SIOUNE AND OGALLA BANDS OF SIOUX INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE CHEYENNE TRIBE OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE HUNKPAPAS BAND OF SIOUX INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE RICARA TRIBE OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE MANDAU TRIBE OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE BELANTSE ETEA OR MINETARLL TRIBE OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE CROW TRIBE OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE OTTOE AND MISSOURI TRIBE OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE PAWNEE TRIBE OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE MAHA TRIBE OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE CHIPPEWAY, SAC AND FAX, MENOMINIE, IOWAY, SIOUX, WINNEBAGO AND A PORTION OF THE OTTOWA, CHIPPEWAY, AND POWATOMIE TRIBES OF INDIANS.

TO PASS A RESOLUTION CONVEYING TO THE PRESIDENT THE OPINION OF THE SENATE THAT DANIEL BISSELL IS ENTITLED TO THE RANK OF COLONEL IN THE U.S. ARMY FROM AUG. 15, 1812, WITH THE BREVET RANK OF BRIGADEER GENERAL FROM MARCH 9, 1814.
TO TABLE A RESOLUTION CONFIRMING THE NOMINATION OF RICHARD C. ANDERSON AND JOHN SARGEANT AS ENVOYS EXTRAORDINARY AND MINISTERS PLENOPOTENTIARY TO THE ASSEMBLY OF THE AMERICAN NATIONS AT PANAMA.

TO POSTPONE THE SENATE BILL TO AUTHORIZE LEGAL REPRESENTAT- -IVES OF THE MARQUIS DE MAISON ROUGE, TO INSTITUTE A SUIT AGAINST THE UNITED STATES, BY PETITION IN THE COURTS, TO TRY THE VALIDITY OF THEIR TITLE.

TO AMEND THE SENATE BILL (APP. 3-3-26), (4 STAT. L. 139), TO PROVIDE FOR A SURVEY OF A ROUTE FOR A CANAL BETWEEN THE ATLANTIC AND THE GULF OF MEXICO; SAID AMENDMENT TO ADD THAT THE PRESIDENT IS AUTHORIZED TO CAUSE A FURTHER SURVEY OF THE COUNTRY BETWEEN HE APPALACHICOLA AND THE MISSISSIPPI RIVERS WITH THE VIEW OF FORMING AN INLAND NAVIGATION BETWEEN THE SAME, AND TO ALSO APPROPRIATE $20,000 TO COVER EXPENSES OF SAME.

TO PASS A RESOLUTION RELATING TO THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA, PROVIDING THAT THE SENATE SHOULD ACT WITH OPEN DOORS ON THE QUESTION OF PENDING REPRESENTATIVES TO PANAMA, AND THE PRESIDENT SHOULD BE REQUESTED TO INFORM THE SENATE IF THE PUBLICATION OF DOCUMENTSON THE SUBJECT WOULD BE OBJECTIONABLE.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION CONFIRMING THE APPOINTMENT OF ROBERT ROTTENGERS AS PURSER IN THE U.S. NAVY AS OF JULY 16, 1825.

TO POSTPONE, INDEFINITELY, CONSIDERATION OF THE RESOLUTION THAT DECLARES THAT THE SENATE HAS THE UNQUESTIONABLE RIGHT TO CALL ON THE PRESIDENT FOR INFORMATION HE POSSESSES WHICH THE SENATE DEEMS NECESSARY TO THE DISCHARGE OF ITS DUTIES, ESPECIALLY CONCERING MATTERS OF SENATE ADVICE AND CONSENT.

TO POSTPONE, INDEFINITELY, CONSIDERATION OF THE RESOLUTION WHICH DECLARES THAT THE TWO SENATE RESOLUTIONS OF THE 15TH INSTANT REQUESTED INFORMATION WHICH THE SENATE DEEMED IMPORTANT TO GUIDE ITS DECISION ON A SUBJECT WITHIN THE SCOPE OF ITS ADVISORY POWE AND DEEPLY INTERESTING TO THE STATES AND THE PEOPLE OF THE UNION; SAID RESOLUTIONS CONCERNED UNITED STATES REPRESENTATION AT THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA AND PUBLICATION OF DOCUMENTS RELATING TO SAID CONGRESS.
TO POSTPONE INDEFINITELY, THE RESOLUTION THAT THE MESSAGE OF THE PRESIDENT, IN ANSWER TO THE TWO SENATE RESOLUTIONS OF THE 15TH INSTANT, DOES NOT GIVE THE SENATE THE INFORMATION IT REQUESTED.

TO POSTPONE INDEFINITELY THE RESOLUTION DECLARING THAT THE SENATE HAS THE SOLE RIGHT TO DETERMINE WHAT SHALL BE THE RULES OF ITS PROCEEDINGS, AND THE PRESIDENT CANNOT INTERFERE WITH SAME WITHOUT VIOLATING THE CONSTITUTIONAL PRIVELEGES OF THE SENATE.

TO PASS THE MOTION TO POSTPONE INDEFINITELY THE RESOLUTION DECLARING THAT THE SENATE HAS THE SOLE RIGHT TO DETERMINE WHAT ARE ITS EXISTING RULES OF PROCEDURE, AND THAT THE PRESIDENT CANNOT OFFICIALLY DECIDE WHAT THE RULES ARE, OR WHETHER ANY PROPOSED MOD OF ACTING IS A DEPARTURE FROM THEM OR WHETHER IT WOULD BE ESSENTIAL TO PUBLIC INTEREST THAT SAME SUPPOSED USAGE OF THE SENATE SHOULD BE PRESUMED UNIMPAIRED.

TO POSTPONE, INDEFINITELY, CONSIDERATION OF THE RESOLUTION PROVIDING THAT IT IS NOT COMPENTENT FOR THE PRESIDENT, ON A CALL FROM THE SENATE, TO DECLINE INFORMATION ON THE GROUNDS THAT HE DISAPPROVES OF THE MODE OF PROCEDURE WHICH THE SENATE PROPOSES TO FLLOW.

TO POSTPONE INDEFINITELY CONSIDERATION OF THE RESOLUTION DECLARING THAT AS THE SENATE HAS NOT BEEN INFORMED BY THE PRESIDENT WHETHER THE PUBLICATION OF THE DOUCMENTS, IN RELATION TO THE PROPOSED MISSION TO THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA, WOULD AFFECT ANY PENDINGNEGOTIATIONS, IT IS EXPEDIENT TO PROCEED TO THE DISCUSSION OF THE SUBJECT OF THE MISSION WITH CLOSED DOORS.

TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION THAT THE DISCUSSION UPON THE PROPOSED MISSION TO PANAMA, AND THE CONFIDENTIAL COMMUNI- -CATIONS UPON SAME, BE HELD WITH CLOSED DOORS, SAID AMENDMENT TO ELIMINATE THE WORDS TO HOLD SAID DISCUSSION BEHIND CLOSED DOORS.

TO ADOPT THE AMENDED RESOLUTION THAT THE SENATE CANNOT CONSIDER THE QUESTION OF APPOINTING MINISTERS TO THE CONGRESS AT PANAMA UNTIL RECEIVING INFORMATION NECESSARY TO DETERMINE WHETHER THE SUBJECT MUST BE DISCUSSED BEHIND CLOSED DOORS.

TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION DECLARING THAT AS THE SENATE HAS NOT BEEN INFORMED BY THE PRESIDENT WHETHER THE PUBLICATION OF THE DOCUMENTS  IN RELATION TO THE PROPOSED MISSION TO THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA WOULD AFFECT ANY PENDING NEGOTIATIONS, IT IS EXPEDIENT TO ROCEED TO THE DISCUSSION OF SAID MISSION WITH CLOSED DOORS, BY STRIKING OUT ALL AFTER THE FIRST RESOLVING CLAUSE.

TO ADOPT THE AMENDMENT AS A SUBSTITUTE FOR THE ORIGINAL RESOLUTION, WHICH AMENDMENT PROVIDES THAT THE SENATE CANNOT FIND IN THE ANSWER OF THE PRESIDENT ANY DISTINCT INFORMATION THAT THE PUBLICATION OF THE COMMUNICATIONS RELATING TO THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA WOULD OR WOULD NOT BE PREJUDICAL TO EXISTING NEGOTIATIONS, THEY FEEL THAT THE PRESIDENT DOES NOT DESIRE THESE MAY BE MADE PUBLIC.

TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF THE SENATE BILL (APP. 5-20-26), TO PAY JAMES DICKSON AND COMPANY A SUM AS A MOIETY OF THE PROCEEDS ON CERTAIN FOODS IMPORTED BY THEM IN 1812 AND SOLD BY THE UNITED STATES.
TO CONSIDER THE RESOLUTION CONCERNING THE EXPEDIENCY OF SENDING MINISTERS TO THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA.

TO AMEND THE HOUSE BILL (APP. 3-14-26), (4 STAT L 149), TO MAKE APPROPRIATIONS FOR CERTAIN FORTIFICATIONS OF THE U.S. FOR FISCAL 1826, BY ELIMINATING AN APPROPRIATION OF $17,000 OF LAND AND THE RIGHT OF WAY ON THROG'S POINT, LONG ISLAND SOUND.

TO ADJOURN, MOTION MADE DURING CONSIDERATION OF A RESOLUTION CONFIRMING THE NOMINATION OF RICHARD ANDERSON AND JOHN SARGEANT AS ENVOYS EXTRAORDINARY AND MINISTERS PLENOPOTENTIARY TO THE ASSEMBLY OF THE AMERICAN NATIONS AT PANAMA.
TO ADJOURN.
TO POSTPONE CONSIDERATION OF THE RESOLUTION CONCERNING THE EXPEDIENCY OF PENDING MINISTERS TO THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA, AND TO MAKE THE SAME ORDER OF THE DAY ON FRIDAY NEXT.

TO EXCUSE SENATOR REED FROM VOTING ON THE RESOLUTION THAT IT IS NOT EXPEDIENT FOR THE U.S. TO SEND ANY MINISTERS TO THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA BEFORE IT SHALL HAVE RECEIVED INFORMATION REGARDING THE SUBJECT, TO WHICH THE ATTENTION OF THE CONGRESS SHALL BE DIECTED.

TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION TO SEND A MINISTER TO THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA, BY ADDING THE FOLLOWING:  "IT IS NOT EXPEDIENT FOR THE U.S. TO SEND MINISTERS TO THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA BEFORE IT RECEIVES INFORMATION ON THE FOLLOWING POINTS:  (1) THE SUBJECTS TO BE ISCUSSED BY THE CONGRESS, (2) THE SUBSTANCE AND POWERS TO BE GIVEN TO THE RESPECTIVE REPRESENTATIVES, (3) THE MODE OF ORGANIZING THE CONGRESS, AND (4) THE MODE OF ACTION IN DECIDING THE QUESTION WHICH MAY BE SUBMITTED.
TO ADOPT THE RESOLUTION THAT IT IS NOT WITHIN THE CONSTITUTIONAL POWER OF THE FEDERAL GOVERNMENT TO APPOINT REPRESENTATIVES TO REPRESENT THE UNITED STATES AT THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA.
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION THAT IT IS NOT EXPEDIENT, AT THIS TIME, FOR THE UNITED STATES TO SEND ANY MINISTERS TO THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA.

TO DISCHARGE THE COMMITTEE ON FOREIGN RELATIONS FROM FURTHER CONSIDERATION OF THE MESSAGE OF THE PRESIDENT OF DEC. 26, 1825, NOMINATING RICHARD C. ANDERSON, JOHN SARGEANT AND WILLIAM B. ROCHESTER TO BE MINISTERS REPRESENTING THE UNITED STATES AT THE CONGESS OF PANAMA.
TO ADJOURN.

TO PROCEED TO THE CONSIDERATION OF PRESIDENT'S MESSAGE OF DEC. 26, 1825, NOMINATING RICHARD C. ANDERSON, JOHN SARGEANT AND WILLIAM B. ROCHESTER AS MINISTERS REPRESENTING THE U.S. AT THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA.
TO ADVISE AND CONSENT TO THE NOMINATION OF RICHARD C. ANDERSON, AS A MINISTER TO REPRESENT THE U.S. AT THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA.
TO ADVISE AND CONSENT TO THE NOMINATION OF JOHN SARGEANT, AS MINISTER TO REPRESENT THE U.S. AT THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA.
TO ADVISE AND CONSENT TO THE NOMINATION OF WILLIAM B. ROCHESTER, AS A MINISTER TO REPRESENT THE U.S. AT THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA.
TO ADJOURN, MOTION MADE DURING CONSIDERATION OF RESOLUTION ON THE EXPEDIENCY OF SENDING MINISTERS TO THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA.
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION THAT THE INJUNCTION OF SECRECY BE REMOVED FROM THE JOURNAL OF THE SENATE, ON THE SUBJECT OF SENDING MINISTERS TO THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA.
TO AMEND THE HOUSE BILL (APP. 3-25-26), (4 STAT. L. 150), TO MAKE MILITARY APPROPRIATIONS FOR 1826, SAID AMENDMENT TO ELIMINATE THE APPROPRIATION FOR THE CONTINUATION OF THE CUMBERLAND ROAD.

TO AMEND THE HOUSE BILL (APP. 3-25-26), (4 STAT. L. 150), TO MAKE MILITARY APPROPRIATIONS FOR 1826, SAID AMENDMENT TO ELIMINATE THE APPROPRIATION TO DEFRAY THE EXPENSES INCIDEN- -TAL TO SURVEYS FOR THE FORMATION OF ROADS AND CANALS.

TO POSTPONE CONSIDERATION OF RESOLUTION WHICH PROVIDES THAT THE INJUNCTION OF SECRECY BE REMOVED FROM THE PRESIDENT'S MESSAGE OF DEC. 26, 1825, RELATING TO THE PROPOSED ASSEMBLY OF AMERICAN NATIONS AT PANAMA, AND FROM ALL EXECUTIVE COMMUNICATIONS, AND DOUMENTS SENT TO SENATE REGARDING SAME.

TO PASS A RESOLUTION PROVIDING THAT THE INJUNCTION OF SECRECY BE REMOVED FROM THE PRESIDENTS MESSAGE OF DEC. 26, 1825, RELATING TO THE PROPOSED ASSEMBLY OF AMERICAN NATIONS AT PANAMA, AND FROM ALL EXECUTIVE COMMUNICATIONS, AND DOCUMENTS SENT TO THE SENAT REGARDING SAME.

TO AMEND THE SENATE BILL TO SECURE THE ACCOUNTABILITY OF DISBURSING OFFICERS AND OTHERS, SAID AMENDMENT BEING THAT NO PERSON INDEBTED TO THE UNITED STATES SHALL BE APPOINTED TO APPOINTED TO ANY POSITION THAT WOULD INVOLVE THE HANDLING OF PUBLIC MONEY.

TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF A HOUSE BILL, (APP. 4-5-26, STAT. 6-6 339), GRANTING A TOWNSHIP OF THE PUBLIC LANDS FOR THE BENEFIT OF THE INCORPORATED KENTUCKY ASYLUM FOR TEACHING THE DEAF AND THE DUMB.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION CONFIRMING THE NOMINATION OF CHARLES J. INGERSOLL AS U.S. ATTORNEY FOR THE EASTERN DISTRICT OF PENNSYLVANIA, FOR THE TERM OF FOUR YEARS, FROM FEB. 28, 1826.

TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF A RESOLUTION PROPOSING AN AMENDMENT TO THE U.S. CONSTITUTION, THAT NO PERSON WHO SHALL HAVE BEEN ELECTED TO THE OFFICE OF PRESIDENT OF THE U.S. A SECOND TIME, SHALL AGAIN BE ELIGIBLE TO THAT OFFICE.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION CONFIRMING THE NOMINATION OF GEORGE HAY AS JUDGE OF THE U.S. FOR THE EASTERN DISTRICT OF VIRGINIA.

TO ADOPT A RESOLUTION PROPOSING AS AN AMENDMENT TO THE CONSTITUTION OF THE U.S., THAT NO PERSON WHO SHALL HAVE BEEN ELECTED TO THE OFFICE OF PRESIDENT OF THE U.S. A SECOND TIME SHALL AGAIN BE ELIBIBLE TO THAT OFFICE.

TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION THAT THE COMMITTEE ON FINANCE BE INSTRUCTED TO REPORT A BILL PROVIDING FOR A REPEAL OF THE DUTY ON IMPORTED SALT IN ACCORD WITH THE ESTIMATES AND PROBABLE REVENUE OF THE CURRENT YEAR, SAID AMENDMENT TO ELIMINATE:  "TO REPORT A BIL" AND INSERT:  "TO ENQUIRE INTO THE EXPEDIENCY OF PROVIDING."

TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF THE SENATE BILL WHICH PROVIDES FOR THE REMOVAL OF HULKS SUNK ON ORDER OF THE AMERICAN COMMANDER, AND NOT THOSE SUNK BY THE ENEMY, IN THE SAVANNAH RIVER, DURING THE WAR WITH GREAT BRITIAN.
TO TABLE THE RESOLUTION TO RATIFY A TREATY BETWEEN THE UNITED STATES AND THE CREEK NATION OF INDIANS OF JAN. 1826.

TO ADOPT THE RESOLUTION REQUESTING THE PRESIDENT TO LAY BEFORE THE SENATE THE TREATY MADE WITH THE CREEK INDIANS IN FEBRUARY 1825, AND SUCH EVIDENCE HE MAY HAVE THAT THE TREATY SHOULD NOT NOW BE BINDING.

TO AMEND THE HOUSE BILL ENTITLED "AN ACT TO FURTHER AMEND THE JUDICIAL SYSTEM OF THE U.S."; SPECIFYING THE MAKEUP OF THE 7TH THRU 10TH CIRCUITS, AND THE ASSIGNMENT OF SUPREME COURT JUSTICES THEREOF AND TO REPLACE THE SECTION WITH AN ALTERED LIST OF DISTRCTS.

TO AMEND THE JUDICIAL BILL SO TO ADD THAT THE CONCURRENCE OF AT LEAST SEVEN JUSTICES OF THE SUPREME COURT IS NECESSARY IN ALL DECISIONS AFFECTING CHANGES IN THE LAW OR CONSTITUTION OF A STATE, OR OF THE U.S.
TO AMEND THE JUDICIAL BILL SO AS TO ADD THAT THE MARSHALL OR OTHER MINISTERIAL OFFICERS OF A GIVEN STATE SHALL BE GOVERNED BY THE LAWS OF SAID STATE, EXCEPT IN CASES AFFECT- -ING THE PUBLIC REVENUE.
TO TABLE THE RESOLUTION THAT THE PRESIDENT OF THE SENATE AND SPEAKER OF THE HOUSE DO ADJOURN THEIR RESPECTIVE HOUSES ON A MONDAY IN NEXT MAY.

TO RECOMMIT THE JUDICIAL BILL TO COMMITTEE WITH INSTRUCTIONS TO REPORT IT BACK WITH AMENDMENTS WHICH WILL REMOVE ANY EXISTING GRIEVANCE WITHOUT AN INCREASE IN THE NUMBER OF JUDGES OF THE SUPREME COURT.
TO AMEND THE JUDICIAL BILL BY LIMITING THE NUMBER OF SUPREME COURT ASSOCIATE JUSTICES TO EIGHT.

TO AMEND THE JUDICIAL BILL TO ADD THAT ANY JUDGE OF THE SUPREME COURT OF THE U.S., BEFORE WHOM ANY CASE HAS BEEN, OR SHALL HEREAFTER BE TRIED, SHALL NOT GIVE HIS OPINION OF THE CASE IN THE SUPREME COURT.
TO AMEND THE JUDICIAL BILL BY PROVIDING THAT NO MEMBER OF EITHER HOUSE OF CONGRESS SHALL APPEAR, OR ACT IN THE U.S. SUPREME COURT AS AN ATTORNEY, DURING THE PERIOD FOR WHICH HE SERVES OFFICE.
TO PASS THE JUDICIAL BILL.

TO AGREE TO THE RESOLUTION THAT THE 31ST RULE OF THE SENATE, AS MODIFIED, BE RESTORED TO ITS ORIGINAL FORM, AS BEFORE MODIFICATION, WHICH HAS THE EFFECT OF RETURNING THE POWER OF APPOINTING COMMITTEES TO THE SENATE.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION THAT THE CONTROL OVER THE JOURNAL OF PROCEEDINGS BE TAKEN FROM THE PRESIDENT OF THE SENATE AND RESTORED TO THE SENATE ITSELF.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION CONFIRMING THE APPOINTMENT OF AMOS BINNEY AS NAVY AGENT IN BOSTON.
TO AMEND THE CREEK INDIAN RESOLUTION SO AS TO DECLARE VOID THE FIRST ARTICLE OF THE FEBRUARY, 1825, TREATY WITH THE CREEK INDIANS.

TO AMEND THE CREEK INDIAN RESOLUTION SO AS TO ADD THE FOLLOWING:  (1) TO PROVIDE $30,000 FOR EACH 1000 CREEK INDIANS WILLING TO EMIGRATE WEST OF THE MISSISSIPPI, (2) TO GIVE SUPPORT TO SAID EMIGRANTS AFTER THEIR ARRIVAL AT THEIR DESTINATION AND (2) TO PRVIDE FOR THE APPOINTMENT OF AN AGENT ACCEPTABLE TO THE INDIANS.
TO PASS THE CREEK INDIAN RESOLUTION.

TO PASS THE SENATE BILL (APP. 5-13-1826), (4 STAT. L. 162), THAT AUTHORIZES THE PURCHASE OF 1,000 SHARES OF STOCK BY THE UNITED STATES, IN THE LOUISVILLE AND PORTLAND CANAL CO., ON THE SAME TERMS GRANTED TO OTHER STOCK HOLDERS.
TO RECOMMIT THE SENATE BILL REGARDING THE CLAIM OF ARNOLD STETSON TO THE COMMITTEE ON CLAIMS, WITH INSTRUCTIONS TO REPORT AN AMENDMENT TO PROVIDE INDEMNITY FOR HIS LOSS ON TREASURY VOTES.
TO ADJOURN, MOTION MADE DURING CONSIDERATION OF A MOTION RELATIVE TO THE EXTENT OF THE POWER OF THE EXECUTIVE IN THE APPOINTMENT OF FOREIGN MINISTERS.

TO TABLE THE RESOLUTION THAT THE PRESIDENT OF THE U.S., DOES NOT, WITHOUT THE ADVISE AND CONSENT OF THE SENATE CONSTITUTIONALLY POSSESS EITHER THE RIGHT, OR THE POWER, TO APPOINT AMBASSADORS OR OTHER PUBLIC MINISTERS, EXCEPT WHEN VACANCIES MAY OCCUR IN TE RECESS.
TO ADOPT THE RESOLUTION THAT A SURVEY BE MADE OF CERTAIN ROUTES BETWEEN BALTIMORE AND PHILADELPHIA, FOR A POST ROAD.
TO POSTPONE, INDEFINITELY, THE SENATE BILL TO ESTABLISH A UNIFORM SYSTEM OF BANKRUPTCY THROUGHOUT THE U.S.

TO AMEND A SENATE BILL (APP. 5-13-26), "TO AMEND THE SEVERAL ACTS FOR THE ESTABLISHMENT OF A TERRITORIAL GOVERNMENT IN FLORIDA," SAID AMENDMENT BEING TO EXEMPT THAT ACT GRANTING DIVORCES, FROM CLAUSE WHICH ANNULS AND REPEALS VARIOUS ACTS PASSED BY THE GOERNOR AND COUNCIL OF THE TERRITORY, SO THAT DIVORCES GRANTED IN NOV
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE GREAT AND LITTLE OSAGE TRIBES OF INDIANS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE KANZAS NATION OF INDIANS.

TO AMEND A HOUSE BILL (APP. 5-4-26), (4 STAT. 6. 158), TO MAKE APPROPRIATIONS FOR APPOINTMENT OF A MISSION TO PANAMA, BY ADDING, THAT IN SENDING A MISSION TO PANAMA, TO EXTEND OUR COMMERCIAL RELATIONS, NOTHING IN THIS ACT SHALL BE CONSTRUED AS A DEPARTUR FROM THE SETTLED POLICY OF THIS GOVERNMENT, WHICH IS TO FORM NO EXTANGLING ALLIANCES WITH ANY OTHER NATION.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF THE HOUSE BILL (APP. 5-2-26), (4 STAT. L. 158) MAKING APPROPRIATIONS FOR CARRYING INTO EFFECT THE APPOINTMENT OF A MISSION AT THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA.
TO ADHERE TO THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO THE JUDICIAL BILL, WHICH PROVIDES THAT THE JUDGES OF CIRCUIT COURTS RESIDE WITHIN THEIR RESPECTIVE CIRCUITS.
TO PASS THE HOUSE BILL (APP. 5-4-1826), (4 STAT. L 158), TO MAKE APPROPRIATIONS FOR CARRYING INTO EFFECT THE APPOINTMENT OF A MISSION TO THE CONGRESS OF PANAMA.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION RATIFYING A TREATY OF FRIENDSHIP, COMMERCE, AND NAVIGATION BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE KING OF DENMARK.

TO REFER THE NOMINATION OF ROBERT TRIMBLE AS ASSOCIATE JUSTICE OF THE SUPREME COURT, TO THE COMMITTEE ON JUDICIARY WITH INSTRUCTIONS TO REPORT ON TRIMBLE'S ATTITUDE, WHILE DISTRICT JUDGE OF KENTUCKY, TO EXECUTIONS.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION CONFIRMING THE NOMINATION OF ROBERT TRIMBLE AS AN ASSOCIATE JUSTICE OF THE SUPREME COURT OF THE UNITED STATES.

TO ADOPT A RESOLUTION AUTHORIZING THE SECRETARY OF THE SENATE TO PURCHASE COPIES OF THE JOURNAL OF PAST CONGRESSES, FOR USE BY THE SENATE, AND TO ALSO PURCHASE COPIES OF INGERSOLL'S ABRIDGEMENT OF THE LAWS FOR THE USE OF THE SENATE.

TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF THE SENATE BILL (APP. 3-2-27), (4 STAT. L. 234), TO GRANT A CERTAIN QUANTITY OF LAND TO ILLINOIS FOR A CANAL TO CONNECT THE ILLINOIS RIVER WITH LAKE MICHIGAN.

TO AGREE TO THE REPORT OF THE JUDICIARY COMMITTEE ON THE JUDICIAL BILL, WHICH ADVISES THE SENATE NOT TO GRANT A CONFERENCE TO THE HOUSE REGARDING THE SENATE AMENDMENT AUTHORIZING THE APPOINTMENT OF THREE NEW CIRCUIT JUDGES, WHO ARE REQUIRED TO RESIDE WITIN THEIR CIRCUITS.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF THE HOUSE BILL (APP. 5-20-26), (4 STAT. L. 181), TO MAKE APPROPRIATIONS TO CARRY OUT THE TREATY WITH THE CREEK INDIAN NATIONS.

TO POSTPONE UNTIL THE FIRST MONDAY IN NEXT DECEMBER, FURTHER CONSIDERATION OF THE SENATE BILL TO ESTABLISH CERTAIN COLLECTION DISTRICTS IN THE STATES OF KENTUCKY, OHIO, INDIANA, ILLINOIS, AND MISSOURI.
TO TABLE THE SENATE BILL TO PROVIDE APPROPRIATIONS FOR REMOVAL OF THE BAR AT THE EAST PASS OF THE MOUTH OF THE PASCAGOULA RIVER, AND FOR IMPROVING THE HARBOR THEREOF.
TO TABLE THE SENATE BILL SUPPLEMENTARY TO AN ACT ENTITLED "AN ACT TO REGULATE THE COMMERCIAL INTERCOURSE BETWEEN THE UNITED STATES AND CERTAIN BRITISH COLONIAL PORTS."
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF THE HOUSE BILL (APP. 5-17-26), (4 STAT. L. 168), AN ACT SUPPLEMENTARY TO AN ACT FOR THE GRADUAL INCREASE OF THE NAVY OF THE U.S.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF THE HOUSE BILL (APP. 5-17-26), (4 STAT. L. 169), WHICH PROVIDES FOR THE SUBSCRIPTION OF STOCK IN THE DISMAL SWAMP CANAL CO.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF THE HOUSE BILL (APP. 5-20-26), (4 STAT. L. 178), FOR THE ERECTION OF A PENITENTIARY IN THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA.
TO PASS THE HOUSE BILL (APP. 5-20-26), (4 STAT. L. 178), FOR THE ERECTION OF A PENITENTIARY IN THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA.

TO AMEND THE SENATE BILL (APP. 5-22-26, 6 STAT. 6. 354), FOR THE SETTLEMENT OF THE CLAIM OF JAMES MONROE AGAINST THE U.S., SAID AMENDMENT PROVIDES THAT A CERTAIN SUM BE ALLOWED MR. MONROE IN FULL SETTLEMENT OF ALL CLAIMS INSTEAD OF ANY OTHER SUM HERETOFOE AGREED UPON.
TO READ THE HOUSE BILL (APP. 3-2-27, 4 STAT. 6. 228), FOR THE PRESERVATION AND REPAIR OF THE CUMBERLAND ROAD, FOR A SECOND TIME.

TO AMEND THE HOUSE BILL (APP. 5-20-26, 4 STAT. 6. 180), TO EXTEND THE WIDTH OF THE WASHINGTON CANAL, BY ELIMINATING THE SECOND SECTION, WHICH EMPOWERS THE AFORESAID CANAL COMPANY TO IMPOSE WHARFAGE CHARGES ON ALL ARTICLES, EXCEPT PUBLIC PROPERTY, LANDED HEREON, ON TAKEN FROM THE WHARVES, OR TO LEASE THE WHARVES AND COLLECT THE RENT THEREFROM.
